    "reasoning": "1. Understand the problem statement and the state diagram provided. 2. Identify that we have a six-state FSM with states A through F, each represented by a one-hot encoding using 6 bits (y[5:0]). 3. Map the state transitions according to the given diagram: A(0) -> B(0), A(0) -> A(1), B(0) -> C(0), B(0) -> D(1), etc. 4. Since the interface requires Y1 and Y3 outputs derived from y[1] and y[3], we must determine the logic equations for these outputs based on the state diagram and one-hot encoding. 5. From the state diagram and one-hot representation, we need to identify the conditions under which y[1] and y[3] change. For instance, for Y1 = y[1], we need to check transitions leading to changes in y[1] and create logical expressions for those transitions. 6. Apply Karnaugh map analysis or direct inspection to derive simplified Boolean expressions for Y1 and Y3. 7. Ensure the module uses proper SystemVerilog syntax with all signals declared as 'logic'. 8. Avoid use of 'unique', 'inside', or explicit sensitivity lists in always blocks except for 'always @(*)'. 9. Confirm that all combinational logic is covered using 'always @(*)'.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input [5:0] y,\n    input w,\n    output logic Y1,\n    output logic Y3\n);\n\n    // Derive next-state logic Y1 and Y3 based on state diagram and one-hot encoding\n    // Y1 corresponds to y[1] (state B)\n    // Y3 corresponds to y[3] (state D)\n    \n    always @(*) begin\n        // Logic for Y1 (next state of y[1])\n        // State B is set when y[0]=1, and transitions to C when w=0\n        // and back to A when w=1\n        Y1 = (y[0] & ~w) | (y[2] & w) | (y[4] & w);\n        \n        // Logic for Y3 (next state of y[3])\n        // State D is set when y[1]=1 and w=0, or when y[3]=1 and w=1\n        Y3 = (y[1] & ~w) | (y[3] & w);\n    end\n    \nendmodule"
